<h2>Problem</h2>
<p>
The three sites were a product of org structure, not user need. Separate accessibility teams, separate mandates, no shared framework — so three separate resources, with overlapping content, conflicting guidance, and no single source of truth. Employees had to know which site to check based on their role, assuming they knew all three existed.
</p>

{% pullquote %}Employees had to know which site to check based on their role, assuming they knew all three existed.{% endpullquote %}

<p>
The consolidation project had organisational weight behind it that previous attempts hadn't. But the underlying disagreement hadn't been resolved — it had been deferred. Getting three audiences onto one site meant making structural decisions that would hold across teams that had historically refused to share a structure. That was the real problem. The IA was just where it would show up.
</p>

{% artifact "Artifact — Team mental model comparison", "Side-by-side comparison of how each team defined onboarding success, surfaced in structured interviews." %}

<h2>Process</h2>
<p>
We started with research on the design section, using a card sort to validate how designers expected accessibility content to be organised. But we had less confidence about the developer and testing content — how it should be structured, and whether it could coexist cleanly with the design section at all. The phased plan was a response to that uncertainty: link out to AllyWay and ACT while we took the time to validate the harder IA decisions properly.
</p>

<p>
That room disappeared when the developer pulled all three sites' content into the build before the IA was ready for it. The scope had effectively tripled without a corresponding change to the brief. We could have paused and pushed for more research time. Given the project constraints, we made the call to extrapolate from what we had.
</p>

{% decisionbox %}We could have paused and pushed for more research time. We didn't — because the organisational momentum behind this project was hard-won and not guaranteed to survive a delay. Extrapolating from a validated pattern was a calculated risk, not a shortcut.{% enddecisionbox %}

<p>
The card sort had surfaced a structure — role-specific education, checklists, and tools — that was intuitive enough to treat as a transferable pattern. We applied it across the develop and test sections, adapting the content groupings to fit each audience's workflow. It wasn't the process we'd designed, but it gave us a defensible foundation and a consistent structure we could explain and stand behind with stakeholders.
</p>

<h2>Solution</h2>
<p>
We shipped a consolidated site with separate role-based pathways for designers, developers, and test engineers — one URL, one search, one source of truth. Duplicative content was reduced. Conflicting guidance was replaced with a consistent structure. Discoverability improved by default.
</p>
<p>
The outcome that mattered most wasn't the site itself. It was that three teams who had never agreed on a shared approach signed off on one. That alignment had been the blocker for years. Shipping gave it somewhere to land.
</p>

